<div id="review_173627209" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/173627209" />
    <a title="Neil" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1666671-neil"><img alt="Neil" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442473216p2/1666671.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/173627209?book_show_action=true">Jun 04, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Neil" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Neil" href="/user/show/1666671-neil">Neil</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer173627209" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17172053347859170781">White exploitation and black rage come to a tragic end in a recording studio in August Wilson&apos;s first play. The mercurial Levee, the patient, philosophical Toledo, and the no-nonsense Ma Rainey are all fascinating characters and now I&apos;d love to see a production of this 1920&apos;s entry from Wilson&apos;s Pittsburgh Cycle (although this one is not set in Pittsburgh). I&apos;d somehow come this far without either reading or seeing one of Wilson&apos;s plays, but I&apos;ll definitely seek out more.</span>
  <span id="freeText17172053347859170781" style="display:none">White exploitation and black rage come to a tragic end in a recording studio in August Wilson's first play. The mercurial Levee, the patient, philosophical Toledo, and the no-nonsense Ma Rainey are all fascinating characters and now I'd love to see a production of this 1920's entry from Wilson's Pittsburgh Cycle (although this one is not set in Pittsburgh). I'd somehow come this far without either reading or seeing one of Wilson's plays, but I'll definitely seek out more.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17172053347859170781" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


